  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Projet de Tissage</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The West African hand woven textile industry is now threatened with extinction. In Burkina Faso 430,000 tonnes of raw cotton are grown annually, but more than 99% is exported leaving only 1000 tonnes for local ?added value&apos; products. This has left around 100,000 weavers, spinners, dyers, tailors and their families unemployed or underemployed and created an exodus of rural people to the cities to seek any form of work. Most clothing and textiles are now imported, or if made locally, use imported yarns, fabric and synthetic components. This project aims to revive handloom textiles in Burkina Faso, and reverse the rural exodus by revitalising and upgrading traditional skills, strengthening technical and management capacity for local production and to design and build up new overseas markets for high value speciality products in the Europe and North America. It seeks to increase the income potential of cotton producing farmers, craft workers, weavers, spinners, dyers and tailors whose livelihoods have been destroyed by the imported cotton clothes which have flooded the market in recent years. The applicant, a UK based design promotion organisation will support the commercial expansion of the Burkina partner company which exports 100% African, 100% handmade and 100% natural fashion and home textiles, and accessories. This follows a successful pilot project, with the aim of creating a sustainable future for skilled craftspeople and families, using a model which can be replicated elsewhere.</narrative>
  </description>
